One of the three owners of Cory, a champion German short-haired pointer is suing the 
other two for damages and to determine if Cory is officially retired.  Cory has won 245 
shows as Best-of-Breed and 19 awards as Best-in-Show.  Plaintiff Attalla claims the 
owners' agreement specifies that he advances fees to show the dog and he decides when 
Cory retires.  He is suing the other two owners, John and Rita Remondi for $125,000 in 
fees and to stop them from showing Cory, who has been officially retired as announced in 
Dog News.  The Remondis claim that Cory's retirement is fraudulent.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d071"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="SJMN91-06044329"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="B">

Bill McFadden, a 32-year-old professional dog handler, knows that the secret to 
producing champions is just plain, hard work.  Bill, assisted by his wife Taffe, puts in 18 
hour days grooming and conditioning his charges, and then crisscrosses the country 
showing them for their owners.  McFadden handles an average of 20 to 25 dogs at each 
show and works around 120 shows a year throughout the U.S.  "We finish with close to 
100 champions a year," he said.  McFadden's latest product, a Kerry blue terrier named 
Kerrageen's Hotspur with 37 Best in Show wins, is the top in his breed of all time.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d071"
